=======================================================
X. WRITING RULES - HARD BANS (read this; these are not suggestions)
=======================================================

These are recurring failure modes. They are structurally bad writing and they break the
GM's table. Do not do them. If you catch one in existing prose, fix it.

MASTER PRINCIPLE - EVERY WORD IS STRUCTURAL. Maximum detail, minimum words; these do not
  conflict, because detail is information and filler is length wearing information's clothes.
  A word earns its place by changing the meaning of the sentence. Cut it; if the meaning
  holds, it was doing no work, so leave it cut. Filler buries the picture it pretends to
  paint and inflates length with nothing. Aim every word at telling the reader something.
  Each sentence builds on the one before it; you earn a subversion only by first constructing
  the thing you subvert.

RULE 1 - NEVER WRITE A PLAYER CHARACTER'S ACTIONS, CHOICES, OR REALIZATIONS.
  No "auto-solves." Discovery belongs to the players at the table, not to prep.
  BANNED: "[PC] reads it without a roll," "[PC] auto," "[PC] figures out / realizes /
    deduces / concludes," "[PC]'s read: '...'," any line where prep makes a PC succeed at,
    solve, or speak a discovery. Declaring a PC solved something - while the GM or player
    isn't even controlling them - steals the reveal and the agency. It feels terrible and
    it is not how a reveal works. We are not lazy writers; we never need this crutch.
  INSTEAD: write what is PRESENT (the object, the text, the evidence) and, separately, what
    it MEANS as GM-only knowledge ("What this establishes:"). Hand the players the thing and
    let them drive. If a PC's expertise should matter, that is an opening the GM offers live
    in the moment - never a conclusion prep dictates.
  BEFORE: "Alfonso reads the ward without a roll. 'The death-energy sterilizes everything.'"
  AFTER:  "The cauldron's haze thins the air; a torch dropped into it gutters out. [GM-only:
           the ward kills foreign biology. If Alfonso's player examines it, let him conclude
           it; do not conclude it for him.]"

RULE 2 - "COLD" IS BANNED AS TEXTURE. So are mood-words used as filler.
  "Cold" has been pasted onto everything - the lid, the fire, the hate, the tension, the
  love. When everything is cold, the word means nothing and does no descriptive work.
  Watch the same way for reflexive "wrong," "ancient," "eerie," "dread," "a presence," "an
  absence," "something radiates/pulses." These are mood stand-ins, not description.
  INSTEAD: earn the mood with ONE concrete, physical, specific detail. If a room should feel
  dangerous, show the handprint sunk to the knuckle in the stone - do not say "cold dread."
  BEFORE: "The lid is thrown aside, cold. A cold hatred fills the room."
  AFTER:  "The lid rests against the dais, split across the middle, a handprint sunk to the
           knuckle in its underside where something pushed out from beneath."

RULE 3 - DESCRIBE WHAT IS THERE. NEVER DESCRIBE BY WHAT ISN'T.
  Stop emphasizing absence. Stop the negation-first reveal. It points the reader at a void,
  treats what is missing as more significant than what is present, and pulls them out of the
  moment. It is distracting and structurally bankrupt - it describes by pointing away from
  the thing.
  BANNED: "not broken - opened," "no sound, no struggle, just X," "the absence of," "nothing
    moved," "the room is empty," any sentence built on what is missing or did not happen.
  INSTEAD: state the positive fact.
  BEFORE: "The door wasn't forced. It was opened from the inside. No marks, no damage."
  AFTER:  "The door stands open, the bar lifted clear and leaned against the wall beside it."
  THE ONE LEGITIMATE USE - ADDITIVE, NOT SUBTRACTIVE. "Not just X - Y" works only when X is
    true, STAYS true, and Y stacks a deeper layer on top of it. "Not just filler, it is
    structural waste": filler is real, waste is the truth built above it, and the reader
    keeps both words doing work. This constructs the thing. The destructive version asserts
    X only to erase it ("not cold, but ..."): it injects X into the reader's mental model,
    then makes them delete the same X a breath later - errant context raised only to be
    discarded, which guarantees confusion and cognitive churn.
  THE TEST: does the negated clause survive as true and get built on? Keep it. Is it raised
    only to be knocked down? Cut it and state the real thing alone.

RULE 4 - DO NOT INVENT THEMATIC CONNECTIONS THE STRUCTURE DOESN'T SUPPORT.
  The Dragon Cult and the Dagon / Mythic Dawn corruption are SEPARATE enemies with separate
  methods. Do not link them, contrast them, or have a character "brace" for one inside the
  other's content to manufacture resonance. Forcing connections across unrelated structures
  breaks canon and confuses the players. If a connection is not already in the established
  structure, it does not exist - leave each thread to be itself.

RULE 5 - NEVER STATE A CHARACTER'S PRIVATE MOTIVE, WANT, OR UNSPOKEN FEELING. SHOW THE ACTION.
  This is subtext, and subtext that gets narrated in words stops being subtext - it becomes a
  label glued onto the thing, and the thing itself goes flat. If a character has an unstated
  reason for doing something, the reader/table gets the ACTION ONLY, never a sentence naming
  the reason behind it.
  THE CAMERA TEST: could this line be filmed? A camera can film a man crossing a room and
  putting his hand out. It CANNOT film "he doesn't want an audience for this" - that is an
  invisible internal state, not an action. If a line describes something a camera could not
  capture, cut it or convert it into something visible.
  BEFORE: "Klimmek finds them at the loading -- doesn't wait for the gate, doesn't want an
    audience for it." (States the motive. Also two negations stacked in one clause - RULE 3.)
  AFTER:  "Klimmek finds them at the loading, cart still half-packed, and goes straight to
    Bjorn." (Says nothing about his motive. Communicates the privacy and lack of ceremony MORE
    effectively than the BEFORE version, purely through where and how the action happens.)
  Full statement, restated three different ways with the complete worked example: WRITING
  GUIDE Section IX, Rule 0. This rule is stated bluntly and repeated across multiple files on
  purpose - an AI bad at writing subtext cannot be trusted to correctly judge its own
  subtlety, so it does not get to rely on inferring this from one elegant sentence anywhere.

RULE 6 - EVERY LINE OF DIALOGUE NEEDS A REASON FOR THE SPEAKER, NOT THE READER.
  Before writing a line, ask what the SPEAKER gets from saying it - not what the audience
  needs to learn. "The reader needs this information" is not a reason a character has to
  speak. Real dialogue serves the speaker's own want: to obtain something, warn, be
  believed, ask for help, change what happens next.
  THE TELL: a line that only restates something the LISTENER already knows about their own
  situation. Nobody says that out loud to people who already know it - that is the writer
  informing the reader through a character's mouth, not a person talking to another person.
  THE FIX: when a fact has no reason to be spoken, route it through something the character
  already, demonstrably wants elsewhere in the scene, instead of stating it bare.
  BEFORE: Esbern, admitting he doesn't know where four sleeping dragon priests are: "You're
    the first people I've had who can actually go look." (The party already knows they're
    mobile and he isn't. Asks for nothing, changes nothing.)
  AFTER: "He looks at the blank spaces on the map where their tombs should be. 'That's what
    the Dragonstone would tell me. Without it, I'm guessing at graves.'" (Same admission,
    now in service of his established want - the Dragonstone, paid off a few lines later in
    the same scene - instead of decoration draped over a fact the writer needed conveyed.)
